description','{\"en\":\"This recording is of a webinar given by Stats4SD. \\r\\n\\r\\nSam Dumble explains some key concepts about precision and variability within a dataset, using a small custom web app to demonstrate the concepts discussed. \\r\\n\\r\\nThe webinar includes: \\r\\n\\r\\n - a brief recap of summary statistics and graphics\\r\\n - a discussion of estimation from samples, including an explanation of what a confidence interval means. \\r\\n - the important difference between precision and accuracy\\r\\n - some discussion of disaggregation of data and what that means for your study design. \\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\nThis webinar was hosted by WorldFish for the Gender & Breeding Postdoctoral Fellow Initiative. It was funded by the CGIAR.\"}','{\"en\":\"<p>This is a recording of a webinar given by Stats4SD. \\r\\n\\r\\n<\\/p><p>Sam Dumble explains some key concepts about precision and variability within a dataset, using a small custom web app to demonstrate the concepts discussed. \\r\\n\\r\\n<\\/p><p>The webinar includes: <\\/p><ul><li>a brief recap of summary statistics and graphics<\\/li><li> a discussion of estimation from samples, including an explanation of what a confidence interval means. <\\/li><li>the important difference between precision and accuracy<\\/li><li>some discussion of disaggregation of data and what that means for your study design. \\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<\\/li><\\/ul><p>This webinar was hosted by WorldFish for the Gender &amp; Breeding Postdoctoral Fellow Initiative. It was funded by the CGIAR.<\\/p>\"}','2019-07-31 13:59:44','2019-07-31 13:59:44'),(828,'App\\Models\\Trove',225,7,'cover_image',NULL,'cover_images/troves/abb266b58014a7e22d52f7a38ab4f207.jpg','2019-07-31 13:59:44','2019-07-31 13:59:44'),(829,'App\\Models\\Trove',226,7,'description','{\"en\":\"This recording is of a webinar given by Stats4SD. \\r\\n\\r\\nAlex Riba and Carlos Barahona discuss the topic of preparing a strategy for data analysis, including the idea of starting with your final report, and working backwards to determine the other parts of your project. \\r\\n\\r\\nIn the second half, Alex presents a case study - an analysis plan developed at the start of a previous project, which clearly defines what information products are required for the final output.\\r\\n\\r\\nThis webinar was hosted by WorldFish for the Gender & Breeding Postdoctoral Fellow Initiative. It was funded by the CGIAR.\"}','{\"en\":\"<p>This is a recording of a webinar given by Stats4SD.&nbsp;<\\/p><p>\\r\\nAlex Riba and Carlos Barahona discuss the topic of preparing a strategy for data analysis, including the idea of starting with your final report, and working backwards to determine the other parts of your project. \\r\\n\\r\\nIn the second half, Alex presents a case study - an analysis plan developed at the start of a previous project, which clearly defines what information products are required for the final output.\\r\\n\\r\\n<\\/p><p>This webinar was hosted by WorldFish for the Gender &amp; Breeding Postdoctoral Fellow Initiative. It was funded by the CGIAR.<\\/p>\"}','2019-07-31 14:01:13','2019-07-31 14:01:13'),(830,'App\\Models\\Trove',226,7,'cover_image',NULL,'cover_images/troves/28be13d53fe3e3beb200f729f5b30130.jpg','2019-07-31 14:01:13','2019-07-31 14:01:13'),(831,'App\\Models\\Trove',227,7,'description','{\"en\":\"This recording is of a webinar given by Stats4SD. \\r\\n\\r\\nCarlos Barahona and Alex Riba discuss issues and challenges relating to data collection and data management. \\r\\n\\r\\nThis webinar is in 2 parts: \\r\\n\\r\\nPart 1: Data Quality\\r\\nPart 2: Digital Data Collection.\\r\\n\\r\\nThis webinar was hosted by WorldFish for the Gender & Breeding Postdoctoral Fellow Initiative. It was funded by the CGIAR.\"}','{\"en\":\"<p>This is a recording of a webinar given by Stats4SD.&nbsp; \\r\\n<\\/p><p>Carlos Barahona and Alex Riba discuss issues and challenges relating to data collection and data management. \\r\\n\\r\\nThis webinar is in 2 parts: \\r\\n\\r\\n<\\/p><ul><li>Part 1: Data Quality\\r\\n<\\/li><li>Part 2: Digital Data Collection.\\r\\n<\\/li><\\/ul><p>\\r\\nThis webinar was hosted by WorldFish for the Gender &amp; Breeding Postdoctoral Fellow Initiative. It was funded by the CGIAR.<\\/p>\"}','2019-07-31 14:02:31','2019-07-31 14:02:31'),(832,'App\\Models\\Trove',227,7,'cover_image',NULL,'cover_images/troves/4e51b96b6f16b668c51ce2ebcf43fbb0.jpg','2019-07-31 14:02:31','2019-07-31 14:02:31'),(833,'App\\Models\\Trove',228,7,'cover_image',NULL,'cover_images/troves/07845a623dfba2bc1669d4652c537fc2.jpg','2019-07-31 14:03:13','2019-07-31 14:03:13'),(834,'App\\Models\\Trove',233,7,'description','{\"en\":\"IndiKit was developed by the Czech INGO People in Need (PIN). It aims to make monitoring and evaluation (M&amp;E) of relief and development interventions easier and better - by helping humanitarian and development workers to use well-formulated project indicators and to correctly collect and analyse the data required for each indicator.\\r\\n\\r\\nIndiKit does not intend to cover an exhaustive list of indicators - its primary focus is on those indicators whose use requires more detailed guidance. PIN has done its best to ensure that this guidance is methodologically correct, useful and concise. IndiKit\'s content is aligned to existing sector standards and was reviewed by M&amp;E and technical specialists from the non-government organizations, Global Clusters, UN agencies and universities. However, keep in mind that the proposed guidance cannot be valid in all contexts \\u2013 you always need to adapt it to the local realities.\"}','{\"en\":\"<p>IndiKit was developed by the Czech INGO People in Need (PIN). It aims to make monitoring and evaluation (M&amp;E) of relief and development interventions easier and better - by helping humanitarian and development workers to use well-formulated project indicators and to correctly collect and analyse the data required for each indicator.\\r\\n\\r\\n<\\/p><p>IndiKit does not intend to cover an exhaustive list of indicators - its primary focus is on those indicators whose use requires more detailed guidance. <\\/p><p>PIN has done its best to ensure that this guidance is methodologically correct, useful and concise. IndiKit\'s content is aligned to existing sector standards and was reviewed by M&amp;E and technical specialists from the non-government organizations, Global Clusters, UN agencies and universities. However, keep in mind that the proposed guidance cannot be valid in all contexts \\u2013 you always need to adapt it to the local realities.<\\/p>\"}','2019-07-31 14:04:37','2019-07-31 14:04:37'),(835,'App\\Models\\Trove',233,7,'cover_image',NULL,'cover_images/troves/38fc45e58be690c4b77549247ba8de35.jpg','2019-07-31 14:04:37','2019-07-31 14:04:37'),(836,'App\\Models\\Trove',233,7,'reviewer_id',NULL,'-1','2019-07-31 14:04:37','2019-07-31 14:04:37'),(837,'App\\Models\\Trove',233,7,'reviewer_id','-1',NULL,'2019-07-31 14:04:37','2019-07-31 14:04:37'),(838,'App\\Models\\Trove',237,7,'description','{\"en\":\"<p><span style=\\\"font-weight: bold;\\\">**Summary: **<\\/span> Sustainability Assessment of Food and Agriculture systems (SAFA). With a view to offer a fair playing field, FAO built on existing efforts and developed a universal framework for Sustainability Assessment of Food and Agriculture systems (SAFA). After 5 years of participatory development (History of SAFA), SAFA has been presented to FAO member countries on 18 October 2013; the SAFA Guidelines, Indicators and Tool and App are freely downloadable from this webpage. <\\/p><p><span style=\\\"font-weight: bold;\\\">\\r\\n\\r\\n**Dimensions Used**<\\/span>: Good Governance; Environmental Integrity; Economic Resilience; Social Wellbeing\\r\\n<\\/p><p><span style=\\\"font-weight: bold;\\\">\\r\\n**Methodology**<\\/span>: Within each dimension a variety of measurements are needed and then compared to ideal practice. There is a somewhat subjective intepretation of where to place each measurement on the assesment scale, which does allow for local contextualisation but may result  in differing results dependent on the user.<\\/p><p><span style=\\\"font-weight: bold;\\\">\\r\\n\\r\\n**Usage**<\\/span>: Dedicated app produced for data entry and analysis. Results mostly displayed through radar charts.\\r\\n<\\/p><p><span style=\\\"font-weight: bold;\\\">\\r\\n**Relevance to CCRP**<\\/span>: Moderate.  Indicators are often worded in very complex and lengthy ways - this is to try to ensure they are specific but this level of specificity may come at the cost of nuance, and the translations of these questions into local languages may require some skill to ensure the meaning is retained.<\\/p>\"}','{\"en\":\"<p><span style=\\\"font-weight: bold;\\\">Summary:<\\/span> Sustainability Assessment of Food and Agriculture systems (SAFA). With a view to offer a fair playing field, FAO built on existing efforts and developed a universal framework for Sustainability Assessment of Food and Agriculture systems (SAFA). After 5 years of participatory development (History of SAFA), SAFA has been presented to FAO member countries on 18 October 2013; the SAFA Guidelines, Indicators and Tool and App are freely downloadable from this webpage. <\\/p><p><span style=\\\"font-weight: bold;\\\">\\r\\n\\r\\nDimensions Used<\\/span>: Good Governance; Environmental Integrity; Economic Resilience; Social Wellbeing\\r\\n<\\/p><p><span style=\\\"font-weight: bold;\\\">\\r\\nMethodology<\\/span>: Within each dimension a variety of measurements are needed and then compared to ideal practice. There is a somewhat subjective intepretation of where to place each measurement on the assesment scale, which does allow for local contextualisation but may result  in differing results dependent on the user.<\\/p><p><span style=\\\"font-weight: bold;\\\">\\r\\n\\r\\nUsage<\\/span>: Dedicated app produced for data entry and analysis. Results mostly displayed through radar charts.\\r\\n<\\/p><p><span style=\\\"font-weight: bold;\\\">\\r\\nRelevance to CCRP<\\/span>: Moderate.  Indicators are often worded in very complex and lengthy ways - this is to try to ensure they are specific but this level of specificity may come at the cost of nuance, and the translations of these questions into local languages may require some skill to ensure the meaning is retained.<\\/p>\"}','2019-07-31 14:06:50','2019-07-31 14:06:50'),(839,'App\\Models\\Trove',237,7,'reviewer_id',NULL,'-1','2019-07-31 14:06:50','2019-07-31 14:06:50'),(840,'App\\Models\\Trove',237,7,'reviewer_id','-1',NULL,'2019-07-31 14:06:50','2019-07-31 14:06:50'),(841,'App\\Models\\Trove',356,7,'deleted_at',NULL,'2019-07-31 14:07:38','2019-07-31 14:07:38','2019-07-31 14:07:38'),(842,'App\\Models\\Trove',246,7,'description','{\"en\":\"<p><span style=\\\"font-weight: bold;\\\">**Summary: ** <\\/span>A description of how to apply the Social Return on Investment (SROI) method in an agroecological context.<\\/p><p><span style=\\\"font-weight: bold;\\\">**Methodology**<\\/span>: Defining the indicators which represent the key social outcomes, assigning monetary value to this and then assigning values based on what extent the outcomes can be attributed to the project, what the negative impacts of the project would be, what externalities may have contributed and what is sustainable.&nbsp;<\\/p><p><span style=\\\"font-weight: bold;\\\">**Usage**<\\/span>: To be constructed on a case by case basis dependent on the key indicators of interest.<\\/p><p><span style=\\\"font-weight: bold;\\\">**Relevance to CCRP**<\\/span>: Moderate. Examples used are not relevant to CCRP - but using a similar approach for evaluating project level outcomes on social criteria could be useful. Particularly the considerations of deadweight, displacement, attribution and drop-off. However there is a strong level of subjectivity to determining actual values for this.<\\/p>\"}','{\"en\":\"<p><span style=\\\"font-weight: bold;\\\">Summary: <\\/span>A description of how to apply the Social Return on Investment (SROI) method in an agroecological context.<\\/p><p><span style=\\\"font-weight: bold;\\\">Methodology<\\/span>: Defining the indicators which represent the key social outcomes, assigning monetary value to this and then assigning values based on what extent the outcomes can be attributed to the project, what the negative impacts of the project would be, what externalities may have contributed and what is sustainable.&nbsp;<\\/p><p><span style=\\\"font-weight: bold;\\\">Usage<\\/span>: To be constructed on a case by case basis dependent on the key indicators of interest.<\\/p><p><span style=\\\"font-weight: bold;\\\">Relevance to CCRP<\\/span>: Moderate. Examples used are not relevant to CCRP - but using a similar approach for evaluating project level outcomes on social criteria could be useful. Particularly the considerations of deadweight, displacement, attribution and drop-off. However there is a strong level of subjectivity to determining actual values for this.<\\/p>\"}','2019-07-31 14:09:03','2019-07-31 14:09:03'),(843,'App\\Models\\Trove',246,7,'reviewer_id',NULL,'-1','2019-07-31 14:09:03','2019-07-31 14:09:03'),(844,'App\\Models\\Trove',246,7,'reviewer_id','-1',NULL,'2019-07-31 14:09:03','2019-07-31 14:09:03'),(845,'App\\Models\\Trove',332,7,'description','{\"en\":\"<p>Information sheet with technical details about Tephrosia Vogelii, a tree with multiple uses, including pest management. <\\/p><p>Taken from the <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.worldagroforestry.org\\/output\\/agroforestree-database\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">The Agroforestree (AFT) Database<\\/a>, a species reference and selection guide for agroforestry trees. <br><span style=\\\"font-weight: bold;\\\"><\\/span><\\/p>\"}','{\"en\":\"<p>Information sheet with technical details about Tephrosia Vogelii, a tree with multiple uses, including pest management. <\\/p><p>Part of the <a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.worldagroforestry.org\