\\":1}]\"}','{\"en\": null}',NULL,NULL,'2019-05-10 14:32:01','2019-09-05 16:40:58',NULL,NULL,'files/data-visualisation-examples_2019-05-10_15:31:59/data-visualisation-examples_2019-05-10_15:31:59.zip',1),(61,'{\"en\":\"Introduction to Analysis of Multi Environment Trials\"}','introduction-to-analysis-of-multi-environment-trials_2019-05-10_15:35:14',NULL,'{\"en\":\"Summary of methods for analysing results from multi environment trials. An appendix outlines R commands for replicating the results shown in the main document.\"}',1,13,'cover_images/troves/dd884269cdcd7965160262686fbd3733.jpg',1,'{\"en\": \"[{\\\"path\\\":\\\"files\\\\/introduction-to-analysis-of-multi-environment-trials_2019-05-10_15:35:14\\\\/2019-05-10_15:35:14_appendices-r.pdf\\\",\\\"storedName\\\":\\\"2019-05-10_15:35:14_appendices-r.pdf\\\",\\\"name\\\":\\\"Appendices R.pdf\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"pdf\\\",\\\"size\\\":897406,\\\"type_id\\\":1},{\\\"path\\\":\\\"files\\\\/introduction-to-analysis-of-multi-environment-trials_2019-05-10_15:35:14\\\\/2019-05-10_15:35:20_attachments-introduction-to-analysis-of-multi-environment-trials-2019-03-04-16-46-25-2019-03-04-16-46-58-appendices-r.docx\\\",\\\"storedName\\\":\\\"2019-05-10_15:35:20_attachments-introduction-to-analysis-of-multi-environment-trials-2019-03-04-16-46-25-2019-03-04-16-46-58-appendices-r.docx\\\",\\\"name\\\":\\\"attachments_introduction-to-analysis-of-multi-environment-trials_2019-03-04 16_46_25_2019-03-04 16_46_58_appendices-r.docx\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"docx\\\",\\\"size\\\":190398,\\\"type_id\\\":1}]\"}','{\"en\": null}',NULL,NULL,'2019-05-10 14:35:20','2019-05-15 06:24:31',NULL,NULL,NULL,1),(62,'{\"en\":\"Analysis of Common Agricultural Designs in R 2\"}','analysis-of-common-agricultural-designs-in-r_2019-05-10_15:35:49',NULL,'{\"en\":\"R tutorials covering standard analyses of data collected from standard on station experimental designs.\\r\\n\\r\\n[UNDER CONSTRUCTION ]\"}',1,13,'cover_images/troves/a13514cf142b0b088d1cb9b5a62f80e1.jpg',1,'{\"en\": \"[]\"}','{\"en\": [{\"path\": \"https://shiny.stats4sd.org/MyBook/index.html\"}]}',NULL,NULL,'2019-05-10 14:35:49','2019-05-28 17:49:28',NULL,NULL,'files/analysis-of-common-agricultural-designs-in-r_2019-05-10_15:35:49/analysis-of-common-agricultural-designs-in-r_2019-05-10_15:35:49.zip',1),(63,'{\"en\":\"Sampling Decision Assistant\"}','sampling-decision-asssistant_2019-05-10_15:39:18',NULL,'{\"en\":\"<p>The Sampling Decision Assistant was developed as a project for UNHCR in 2018. <\\/p><p>The tool is designed to help with the design of sampling schemes. It is for sampling that is done  to provide estimates of the values of characteristics of a population. Such studies are aimed at observing the population and measuring the factors of interest without trying to change anything. This type of study is used for things like profiling populations, setting baselines and assessing the value of indicators\\r\\n at midline or end-line points. \\r\\nThe decisions you make when designing this kind of study are about how you will sample the population.&nbsp; \\r\\n<\\/p><p> It is a website that guides the user through a sequence of decisions that eventually build a sampling scheme. The process can be started, saved and continued on a different session. It contains help about how to use the tool, explanation about statistical issues that are of importance when designing a sampling scheme and a sampling glossary.\\r\\n \\r\\n The resulting set of decisions can be downloaded as a printable file.<\\/p>\"}',1,13,'cover_images/troves/88885b49975797ae267830d5586dbae7.jpg',1,'{\"en\": \"[]\"}','{\"en\": [{\"path\": \"https://unhcr-sampling-assistant.firebaseapp.com/#/home\"}]}',NULL,NULL,'2019-05-10 14:39:18','2019-07-31 10:42:46',NULL,NULL,'files/sampling-decision-asssistant_2019-05-10_15:39:18/sampling-decision-asssistant_2019-05-10_15:39:18.zip',1),(64,'{\"en\":\"What is a representative sample?\"}','what-is-a-representative-sample_2019-05-10_15:46:59',NULL,'{\"en\":\"A 2 min 37 seconds video in English explaining what are the main requirements to select a representative sample\"}',1,13,'cover_images/troves/7ed0e9671a1257c163bccca44f2761ff.jpg',1,'{\"en\": \"[]\"}','{\"en\": null}','{\"en\": \"[{\\\"path\\\":\\\"files\\\\/what-is-a-representative-sample_2019-05-10_15:46:59\\\\/2019-05-10_15:46:59_what-is-a-representative-sample.mp4\\\",\\\"temp_path\\\":\\\"files\\\\/what-is-a-representative-sample_2019-05-10_15:46:59\\\\/2019-05-10_15:46:59_what-is-a-representative-sample.mp4\\\",\\\"storedName\\\":\\\"2019-05-10_15:46:59_what-is-a-representative-sample.mp4\\\",\\\"name\\\":\\\"What is a representative sample.mp4\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"mp4\\\",\\\"size\\\":11254306,\\\"type_id\\\":3}]\"}',NULL,'2019-05-10 14:47:32','2019-05-15 06:31:25',NULL,'RQbyPouT3tE',NULL,1),(66,'{\"en\":\"Data Tree\"}','data-tree_2019-05-10_15:50:06',NULL,'{\"en\":\"<p>Data Tree is a free online course covering research data management, along with ways to engage and share data with business, policymakers, media and the wider public.  It was created particularly for postgraduates, PhD students and early career researchers who want to learn research data management skills, but it can be helpful for researchers, scientists and anyone working with data.&nbsp;<\\/p><p>\\r\\nStats4SD helped create Data Tree in cooperation with the Institute for Environmental Analytics (The IEA). The project was funded by the Natural Environment Research Council (NERC). \\r\\n\\r\\n<\\/p><p>Data Tree Consists of 8 modules:\\r\\n\\r\\n<\\/p><ol><li>Data Management: Context<\\/li><li> Data Management: Practicalities\\r\\n<\\/li><li> NERC\\r\\n4) Data Application: Analysis\\r\\n<\\/li><li>Data Application: Visualisation\\r\\n<\\/li><li>Working with Policy\\r\\n<\\/li><li>Working with Business\\r\\n<\\/li><li>Working with the Media and Public<\\/li><\\/ol>\"}',1,13,'cover_images/troves/2f729a26fc86f706a521cdc61992c848.jpg',1,'{\"en\": \"[]\"}','{\"en\": [{\"path\": \"https://datatree.org.uk/\"}]}',NULL,NULL,'2019-05-10 14:50:06','2019-07-31 10:44:42',NULL,NULL,'files/data-tree_2019-05-10_15:50:06/data-tree_2019-05-10_15:50:06.zip',1),(67,'{\"en\":\"RHoMIS - the Rural Household Multi-Indicator Survey\"}','rhomis-the-rural-household-multi-indicator-survey_2019-05-10_15:51:08',NULL,'{\"en\":\"<p>RHoMIS - the Rural Household Multi-Indicator Survey\\r\\n\\r\\n<\\/p><p>This is a survey that uses standardised indicators to characterise rural households. The main advantage of Rhomis is that it offers the user a questionnaire that includes indicators that have been tested and have been accepted as useful by a large number of users and stakeholders. \\r\\n\\r\\n<\\/p><p>Rhomis offers the ODK forms, the paper questionnaire and some R scripts to pre-process the data collected, but also there is the opportunity of support from the Rhomis team if the user accepts that the data they collect can become part of the multiple country database of rural households characteristics that Rhomis is building.\\r\\n\\r\\nAmong those indicators are the Food Insecurity Experience Scale (FIES), the Household Dietary Diversity Score (HDDS),  the Hunger and Food Insecurity Access Scale (HFIAS), Food Availabilty (FA), and the Progress out of Poverty Index (PPI). All of these have further documentation available from elsewhere and need to be adpated to the context where the survey is to be conducted.\\r\\n\\r\\n<\\/p><p>It is worth exporing their website for more information.<\\/p>\"}',1,13,'cover_images/troves/54b28bbfecac8a413ba34267aa48b707.jpg',1,'{\"en\": \"[]\"}','{\"en\": [{\"path\": \"https://www.rhomis.org/\"}]}',NULL,NULL,'2019-05-10 14:51:08','2019-07-31 10:47:42',NULL,NULL,'files/rhomis-the-rural-household-multi-indicator-survey_2019-05-10_15:51:08/rhomis-the-rural-household-multi-indicator-survey_2019-05-10_15:51:08.zip',1),(68,'{\"en\":\"Farm size and productivity: Lessons from recent literature\"}','farm-size-and-productivity-lessons-from-recent-literature_2019-05